Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables. Most variables are numeric. Too many variables, I'm not going to use all of them.

What is the main features of interest in the dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out what affects the borrowers interest rate.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your features of interest?¶

I expect that the variables will have the strongest effect on the interest rate: BorrowerRate, CreditGrade, Term, LenderYield, ProsperScore, EmploymentStatus, IsBorrowerHomeowner, CurrentlyInGroup, CreditScoreRangeLower, CreditScoreRangeUpper, DebtToIncomeRatio, LoanOriginationDate, BorrowerState.

# Change the datatype of CreditGrade into ordinal category.
ranking = ["AA","A","B","C","D","E","HR","NC"]
creditgrade = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=ranking)
df.CreditGrade = df.CreditGrade.astype(creditgrade)
In [11]:
# Change the data type of ProsperScore into string and then change it into category.
df["ProsperScore"] = df["ProsperScore"].astype(str)
prosper = ["11.0","10.0","9.0","8.0","7.0","6.0","5.0","4.0","3.0","2.0","1.0"]
prosperscore = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True,categories=prosper)
df.ProsperScore = df.ProsperScore.astype(prosperscore)

The distribution of borrower rate is roughly an unimodal shape and it is roughly a right skew shape. The number of borrowers with the interest rate of approximately 0.32 is the largest, followed by 0.15.

The number of lenders with the lender yield of approximately 0.31 is the largest, followed by between 0.14 to 1.15.

The lender yield and Borrower Rate have similar shape of histogram, and LenderYield is a bit more volatile than the Borrower Rate.

There is a strong linear relationship between the borrowers interest rate and the lender yield.

There is a strong linear relationship between the credit score range lower and the credit score range upper, which is reasonable, so I would like to replace these two variables by calculating the average of upper bound and lower bound.

Unexpectly, there's a weak relationship between debt to income ratio to other numeric variables.I thought the debt to income ratio is higher, the ability of paying back wo be lower, the borrower rate would be higher, and the credit score would be lower. I'm not suer yet, I'll dig into it deeper.

There might be a negative linear relationship between the borrower rate and credit score range upper and creditscorerangelower, I'll check it out later.

According to the plots above:

  1. The higher credit grade, the the higher credit score, and the lower interest rate.

  2. The longer term, the higher interest rate.

  3. The lower prosper score, the higher interest rate. There is a roughly positive linear relationship between the prosper score and the credit score, which means the higher prosper score, the higher credit score.

  4. Most likely, homeowners have higher credit score and lower interest rate.

  5. The employed borrowers have a lower interest rate than unemployed borrowers. Borrowers who are employed full-time have a lower interest rate than who are employed part-time, retired or self-employed.

  6. In the past few years, the borrower's interest rate has been fluctuating, but from 2006 to 2009, the credit score has been rising, and has remained at a certain level after 2009.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The borrowers interest rate seems to be highly correlated with the credit score. After plotting the heat map, I noticed a negative linear relationship between the average credit score and the borrowers interest rate. There is no obvious relationship between the borrowers interest rate and other numerical variables. To my surprise, DebtToIncomeRatio does not seem to be related to the borrowing rate.

When I looked at the relationship between borrower interest rates and categorical variables, I noticed that the longer the term, the higher the borrower interest rate. The credit grade looks like a classification grade based on digital credit scores. In addition, the prosper score is somewhat similar to the credit score. The higher the prosper score, the higher the average credit score. Moreover, I found that borrowers who are employed or full-time borrowers have lower borrower interest rates, and homeowners also have lower borrower interest rates.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶


I found out that borrowers who are employed are often homeowners.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

In the bivariate exploration section, I did not see a clear relationship between the variables DebtToIncomeRatio and BorrowerRate. However, in the multivariate exploration section, I noticed that after limiting the range of DebtToIncomeRatio to eliminate outliers, there is a roughly positive linear relationship between the borrowers interest rate and debt to income ratio for each credit level, which is more obvious in credit grade AA, A and B.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Frist of all, I found out that homeowners usually have lower credit scores and higher borrower interest rates. Borrowers employed or employed full-time mostly have higher credit scores and lower borrower interest rates, especially for borrowers employed full-time.

Secondly, I found out that the slope of the average credit score and the borrower rate became steeper as the year increased, which meant that the borrowers interest rate was increasingly sensitive to changes in credit score.

Finally, I found out that the longer the period, the less the plot spread. I think this is because long-term interest rates are more stable than short-term interest rates.
